\section{Microsoft authentication handlers}

Microsoft's Azure Active Directory uses a number-matching
multi-factor authentication (MFA) step in its login flow.
When MFA is required, the server presents a page containing a
number---displayed in a [[<p>]] element with
[[id="validEntropyNumber"]]---that the user must confirm in the
Microsoft Authenticator app on their phone.

This module provides a handler that detects the MFA challenge,
notifies the user of the number, and polls the server by
resubmitting the page's form until the user approves the request.

The same shared session can also carry ordinary API responses.
Those may be XML or JSON error payloads rather than login pages,
so the MFA handler must ignore them instead of trying to parse
every text body as candidate HTML.

Because the MFA page is part of Microsoft's authentication
pipeline---not tied to any particular institution---this handler
works universally.
It identifies the challenge purely by HTML content.
A URL scope can (and should) be provided for security
(\cref{AzureMFAURLScope}).

\subsection{Handler ordering}

The [[AzureMFA]] handler must appear \emph{after} the password
handler in the handler list.
However, thanks to the [[AutologinSession]] architecture
(\cref{WebloginOverview}), the ordering requirement is less
strict than it might seem.

Every intermediate [[session.request()]] call made by other
handlers---for example when [[UGlogin]] submits the password
form---passes through the [[AutologinSession.request()]] method,
which runs the full handler loop on the response.
This means that [[AzureMFA]] will automatically intercept an MFA
challenge even when it appears as an intermediate response
\emph{inside} another handler's login flow.

Usage examples:
\begin{minted}{python}
import weblogin
from weblogin import kth, ladok, microsoft

# KTH with dedicated handlers
session = weblogin.AutologinSession([
    kth.UGlogin(username, password, trigger_url),
    kth.SAMLlogin(),
    microsoft.AzureMFA(url="https://login.ug.kth.se",
                       notification_cmd="notify-send"),
])

# Any university via LADOK's general-purpose handler
session = weblogin.AutologinSession([
    ladok.SSOlogin("KTH Royal Institute of Technology",
                   vars={"username": user, "password": pw}),
    microsoft.AzureMFA(url="https://login.ug.kth.se",
                       notification_cmd="notify-send"),
])
\end{minted}

