\section{The Azure MFA handler}\label{AzureMFAhandler}

<<Azure MFA handler>>=
class AzureMFA(weblogin.AutologinHandler):
  """
  Login handler for Microsoft's Azure MFA number-matching
  challenge.

  Detects the challenge by looking for a ``<p>`` element with
  ``id="validEntropyNumber"`` in an HTML-like response. When
  detected, notifies the user of the number and polls by
  resubmitting the page's form until the challenge is resolved.

  Set the ``WEBLOGIN_MFA_NOTIFICATION`` environment variable to
  a command that will be called with the MFA message as its last
  argument. If unset, the optional ``notification_cmd``
  constructor argument is used instead. If neither is set, the
  handler falls back to ``figlet``, then ``print``.
  """
  MFA_ELEMENT_ID = "validEntropyNumber"
  DEFAULT_POLL_INTERVAL = 2

  def __init__(self, url=None,
               notification_cmd=None,
               poll_interval=DEFAULT_POLL_INTERVAL):
    """
    Creates an MFA handler.

    - ``url``: if set, only intercept responses whose URL starts
      with this string. Recommended for security.
    - ``notification_cmd``: optional command used to notify the
      user. ``WEBLOGIN_MFA_NOTIFICATION`` takes precedence if set.
    - ``poll_interval``: seconds between poll attempts
      (default 2).
    """
    super().__init__()
    self.__url = url
    self.__notification_cmd = notification_cmd
    self.__poll_interval = poll_interval
    self.__logging_in = False

  <<robust markup parsing helper>>

  def need_login(self, response):
    """
    Returns True if the response contains a Microsoft MFA
    number-matching challenge.
    """
    if self.__logging_in:
      return False

    <<check if MFA challenge is present>>

  def login(self, session, response, args=None, kwargs=None):
    """
    Handles the MFA challenge by notifying the user of the
    number and polling until the user approves in the
    Authenticator app.

    Raises AuthenticationError if the MFA page has no form.
    """
    self.__logging_in = True

    try:
      logger.debug(
        "AzureMFA starting for %s",
        weblogin._sanitize_url(response.url),
      )
      <<extract MFA number>>
      <<notify user of MFA number>>
      <<wait for MFA approval>>
    finally:
      self.__logging_in = False
    return final_response
@

We use the same [[self.__logging_in]] guard as the other handlers
to prevent re-entrant invocations while we are polling.
That guard must also be exception-safe: if notification or polling raises, we
still need later MFA challenges to be detectable.
The pages in this flow carry both hidden form fields and the MFA number itself,
so the debug logging must not expose either one.

The tests use mock responses because a live integration test would
require real MFA interaction.

