\subsection{Robust markup parsing}\label{AzureMFAParseMarkup}

Three places in the handler need to turn an HTTP response into a
parsed [[lxml]] tree: the detection check in [[need_login()]], the
number extraction in [[login()]], and the form extraction during
polling.
A naive [[html.fromstring(response.text)]] in those spots breaks
in two distinct ways.

First, a shared authenticated session may carry ordinary API
responses---SharePoint REST, for example, returns XML error bodies
on a [[403]].
Parsing every text body as HTML would therefore be handler
overreach: such bodies are not MFA pages, and the correct answer
is simply \enquote{not for us}.

Second, real MFA pages can arrive as XHTML beginning with an XML
declaration that names an encoding.
[[lxml.html.fromstring()]] rejects such declarations when given a
Unicode string, because the declared encoding and the string's own
encoding might disagree; bytes side-step the conflict by letting
the parser honour the declaration directly.

The helper below addresses both problems in one place.
It treats an explicit non-HTML [[Content-Type]] as an immediate
negative when [[require_html]] is set, but is lenient when the
header is missing or empty---some authentication endpoints are
sloppy about metadata, and we do not want to miss a real MFA page
on that basis alone.
Bodies we do inspect are read as bytes via [[response.content]],
falling back to [[response.text]] only when [[content]] is absent
(useful for hand-rolled mocks).
A parser failure returns [[None]] rather than propagating; the
callers each decide what \enquote{unparseable} means in their
context.
<<robust markup parsing helper>>=
def _parse_markup(self, response, require_html=False):
  headers = getattr(response, "headers", {}) or {}
  content_type = headers.get("Content-Type", "")
  if require_html and content_type \
      and "html" not in content_type.casefold():
    return None

  body = getattr(response, "content", None)
  if not body:
    body = response.text
  if not body:
    return None

  try:
    return html.fromstring(body)
  except (etree.ParserError, TypeError, ValueError):
    return None
@


\subsection{Detecting the MFA challenge}\label{AzureMFAURLScope}

The handler first checks whether the response falls within the
configured URL scope.
Without a scope, any page passing through the session that
happens to contain a [[<p id="validEntropyNumber">]] element
would trigger MFA notification and start a polling loop.
A malicious or coincidental page could exploit this.
Scoping to the known authentication endpoint avoids the problem.

If no URL was configured, the handler checks every response---use
this only when the MFA endpoint is not known ahead of time.

Once the URL passes, we delegate to [[_parse_markup]]
(\cref{AzureMFAParseMarkup}) with [[require_html=True]] so that
non-HTML responses are dismissed without a parse attempt.
A [[None]] result means \enquote{not an MFA page}, so the
detection returns [[False]] in that case.
<<check if MFA challenge is present>>=
if self.__url is not None \
    and not response.url.startswith(self.__url):
  return False

doc_tree = self._parse_markup(response, require_html=True)
if doc_tree is None:
  return False

elements = doc_tree.xpath(
  f"//p[@id='{self.MFA_ELEMENT_ID}']"
)
has_challenge = len(elements) > 0
if has_challenge:
  logger.debug(
    "AzureMFA detected challenge at %s",
    weblogin._sanitize_url(response.url),
  )
return has_challenge
@

