\subsection{Extracting the MFA number}

Once we know the MFA challenge is present, we extract the number
from the element's text content.
We reuse [[_parse_markup]] (\cref{AzureMFAParseMarkup}) so the
same XHTML-and-encoding handling applies here, but at this point a
parse failure is no longer a harmless \enquote{not for us}
answer: the response already passed the detection check, so it
claimed to be an MFA page but no longer has the expected shape.
We therefore raise a clear authentication error instead of leaking
parser internals.
<<extract MFA number>>=
doc_tree = self._parse_markup(response)
if doc_tree is None:
  raise weblogin.AuthenticationError(
    "MFA page could not be parsed"
  )

try:
  element = doc_tree.xpath(
    f"//p[@id='{self.MFA_ELEMENT_ID}']"
  )[0]
except IndexError:
  raise weblogin.AuthenticationError(
    "MFA page has no number to display"
  )

number = element.text_content().strip()
mfa_message = f"MFA: {number}"
@

The byte-first parsing must also work in the full login path,
not only in [[need_login()]].
A real MFA page can arrive as XHTML with an XML declaration, and
[[login()]] must extract the number from such a page just as it
would from a plain HTML one.

<<test functions>>=
def test_login_handles_xhtml_mfa_page(monkeypatch):
  calls = []
  monkeypatch.delenv(
    "WEBLOGIN_MFA_NOTIFICATION", raising=False
  )
  stub_successful_mfa_poll(monkeypatch)

  def fake_run(cmd, check=False):
    calls.append((cmd, check))

  monkeypatch.setattr(microsoft.subprocess, "run", fake_run)

  handler = AzureMFA(notification_cmd="xmessage")
  handler.login(
    object(),
    MockResponse(
      XHTML_MFA,
      headers={
        "Content-Type": "application/xhtml+xml; charset=utf-8"
      }
    )
  )

  assert calls == [(["xmessage", "MFA: 42"], False)]
