\subsection{Notifying the user}\label{AzureMFANotification}

The notification mechanism is primarily controlled by the
[[WEBLOGIN_MFA_NOTIFICATION]] environment variable.
When that variable is not set, callers may provide
[[notification_cmd]] to the constructor instead.
In both cases, the command is split into arguments and the MFA
message is appended as the final argument.
This keeps the shell-facing interface flexible while still giving
application code a direct way to request a particular notifier.

The environment variable takes precedence so that users can
override a program's default without editing code.
This makes the mechanism completely flexible:
\begin{description}
\item[Desktop notification]
  [[WEBLOGIN_MFA_NOTIFICATION="notify-send 'Azure MFA'"]]
\item[X11 dialog]
  [[WEBLOGIN_MFA_NOTIFICATION=xmessage]]
\item[KDE dialog]
  [[WEBLOGIN_MFA_NOTIFICATION="kdialog --msgbox"]]
\item[Zulip message to phone]
  [[WEBLOGIN_MFA_NOTIFICATION="zulip-send --stream
  notifications --subject MFA"]]
\end{description}

If the variable is not set, we try to display the number using
[[figlet]] for a large, visible terminal output.
If [[figlet]] is not installed, we fall back to plain [[print]].
<<notify user of MFA number>>=
notification_cmd = os.environ.get(
  "WEBLOGIN_MFA_NOTIFICATION"
)

if notification_cmd is None:
  notification_cmd = self.__notification_cmd

if notification_cmd:
  logger.debug("AzureMFA using notification command")
  subprocess.run(
    shlex.split(notification_cmd) + [mfa_message]
  )
else:
  try:
    logger.debug("AzureMFA using figlet notification fallback")
    subprocess.run(["figlet", mfa_message], check=True)
  except FileNotFoundError:
    logger.debug("AzureMFA using plain stdout notification fallback")
    print(mfa_message)
@

The notification path is sensitive to process environment, so the
tests explicitly set or unset [[WEBLOGIN_MFA_NOTIFICATION]].
This prevents a developer's shell configuration from changing test
outcomes.

