\subsection{Polling for MFA approval}

After notifying the user, we wait for them to approve the MFA
request in their Authenticator app.
The MFA page contains a form with hidden input fields (at least
[[AzureMfaAuthentication]] and [[Context]]).
We resubmit this form repeatedly until the response no longer
contains the MFA challenge element---meaning the server accepted
the approval from the phone.

The critical design decision is \emph{how} we submit the poll
requests.
Calling [[session.request()]] would route each poll response
through the [[AutologinSession]] handler loop.
Since the MFA page is typically served from a domain that other
handlers also recognize (for instance, [[UGlogin]] watches
[[login.ug.kth.se]]), those handlers would fire and attempt to
re-submit credentials on every poll iteration.

We avoid this by calling [[requests.Session.request(session,
...)]] directly---the undecorated parent method---which uses the
session's cookies and TLS state without invoking any handler
logic.
<<wait for MFA approval>>=
current_response = response

while True:
  time.sleep(self.__poll_interval)
  <<extract form from current response>>
  <<post form, bypassing handler loop>>
  <<check if MFA challenge is resolved>>

final_response = current_response
@

To extract the form data, we parse the page and collect all
[[<input>]] elements, the same approach used by the other
handlers in this package.
<<extract form from current response>>=
doc_tree = self._parse_markup(current_response)
if doc_tree is None:
  raise weblogin.AuthenticationError(
    "MFA page could not be parsed"
  )

try:
  form = doc_tree.xpath("//form")[0]
except IndexError:
  raise weblogin.AuthenticationError(
    "MFA page has no form to submit"
  )

data = {}
for var in form.xpath(".//input"):
  if var.name:
    data[var.name] = var.value or ""

action_url = urllib.parse.urljoin(
  current_response.url, form.action
)
@

As explained above, we call the parent class method directly to
bypass the handler loop.
<<post form, bypassing handler loop>>=
logger.debug(
  "AzureMFA polling %s",
  weblogin._sanitize_url(action_url),
)
current_response = requests.Session.request(
  session, form.method, action_url, data=data
)
@

We check whether the MFA challenge has been resolved by looking
for the disappearance of the [[validEntropyNumber]] element.
An empty body or otherwise unparseable response also ends the
loop: [[_parse_markup]] already covers both cases by returning
[[None]], so we use that as the single termination signal here.
<<check if MFA challenge is resolved>>=
resolved_tree = self._parse_markup(current_response)
if resolved_tree is None:
  break

elements = resolved_tree.xpath(
  f"//p[@id='{self.MFA_ELEMENT_ID}']"
)
if len(elements) == 0:
  logger.debug(
    "AzureMFA challenge resolved at %s",
    weblogin._sanitize_url(current_response.url),
  )
  break
@

If polling fails, the handler must still leave the re-entrancy guard in a clean
state so that a later MFA challenge can be handled normally.

<<test functions>>=
def test_mfa_resets_logging_in_after_exception(monkeypatch):
  monkeypatch.delenv(
    "WEBLOGIN_MFA_NOTIFICATION", raising=False
  )

  def fail_request(*args, **kwargs):
    raise RuntimeError("boom")

  monkeypatch.setattr(
    microsoft.requests.Session, "request", fail_request
  )
  monkeypatch.setattr(
    microsoft.time, "sleep", lambda seconds: None
  )
  monkeypatch.setattr(
    microsoft.subprocess, "run", lambda *args, **kwargs: None
  )

  handler = AzureMFA()
  response = MockResponse(MFA_HTML)

  try:
    handler.login(object(), response)
  except RuntimeError:
    pass
  else:
    assert False

  assert handler.need_login(response)
@
